===Etymology===
{{etyl|enm}} {{term|heroun|lang=enm}}, {{term|heiron|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|xno}} {{term|hairon|lang=xno}}, {{term|heiron|lang=xno}} (cf. modern French {{term|héron|lang=fr}}), from Old Low Franconian *''heigro'' (cf. {{etyl|goh|-}} {{term|heigir|lang=goh}}, {{term|heigaro|lang=goh}}), from {{proto|Germanic|xaiʒarōn}} (cf. Swedish {{term|häger|lang=sv}}, Danish {{term|hejre|lang=da}}), dissimilated form of {{proto|Germanic|xraiʒrōn}} (cf. {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|hragra|hrāgra|lang=ang}}, {{etyl|fry|-}} {{term|reager|lang=fry}}, {{etyl|nl|-}} {{term|reiger|lang=nl}}, {{etyl|de|-}} {{term|Reiher|lang=de}}), from {{proto|Indo-European|kroikro}} (cf. {{etyl|cy|-}} {{term|crëyr|lang=cy||heron}}), from *''(s)ker''- (cf. {{etyl|cy|-}} {{term|cryg|lang=cy||hoarse}}, {{etyl|lt|-}} {{term|krỹkšti|lang=lt||to shriek}}, {{etyl|cu|-}} {{term|кричати|tr=kričati|lang=cu||to cry out}}, {{term|крикъ|tr=krikŭ|lang=cu||screaming}}, {{etyl|grc|-}} {{term|κρίζω|tr=krízō|lang=grc||to creak}}, aorist {{term|κρίκε|tr=kríke|lang=grc||it creaked}}).

